As many advancement are being made in AI technologies i was questioning how much of it can be pushed in robotics. Specifically for FRC. Object detection is pretty much common and a known use but what about on the fly paths with robot detections or a fully auton robot with sensors to pick and score game pieces strategically and pathfind without a driver. I think i’ve heard people using robot detection for stuff (would really be appreciated if you could provide an example). Am i too far into the future here or robots will become fully autonomus in the next 5 years?

There were a lot of great responses in the following topic, I’d check them out!

Do you think AI will effect the future of FIRST General Forum
With how quick AI is evolving, especially in the mechanical design front, as well as it becoming more widely available, do you think AI will effect the future of FIRST and if so how will it be used?
kuzeyatay:

Am i too far into the future here or robots will become fully autonomus in the next 5 years?

There seems to be a lot of interest in AI scouting, so I believe every scout should be fearful of losing their job. Aside from scouting (and maybe awards), I don’t see AI inducing large changes in FIRST or FRC.

TrevDay:

believe every scout should be fearful of losing their job

In the same way everyone in the world is gonna lose their job to AI, right?

AI is great at doing repetitive, boilerplate, or very objective-based tasks. Great for summaries to work quickly.

It cannot however, tell you how to win on Einstein, win a regional playoff match, or bat better than a 500 on a regular quals match without a lot of coaching.

If AI Scouting could track all of the objective data (shot X times, made Y, missed Z, etc…) and my kids could focus on scouting more subjective data (robot stability, driver skill, etc…) then they would have more time for strategy and analysis. Scouters get burned out when asked to track too many things in the limited time of a match.

","post_number":9,"post_type":1,"posts_count":39,"updated_at":"2025-01-23T20:13:24.759Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":7,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":4,"reads":595,"readers_count":594,"score":154.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":483243,"topic_slug":"how-much-ai-can-and-is-being-used-in-frc","display_username":"Skye Leake","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":61162,"username":"PanicLemming","name":null,"avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/paniclemming/{size}/234749_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":true,"admin":false,"staff":true,"user_id":19235,"hidden":false,"trust_level":4,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Pretengineer"},"post_url":"/t/how-much-ai-can-and-is-being-used-in-frc/483243/9","custom_user_title":"Pretengineer","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3490935,"name":"","username":"Randomness57","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/r/f05b48/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-01-23T20:13:38.059Z","cooked":"

3015 last year could do fully autonomous cycles with no other teams on the field. I expect that vision processing will continue to get better and more powerful, and that teams will push more and more autonomy into the robots.

I don’t expect teams to use onboard or on-laptop models to drive the entire robot for a full match. I think very specific teams could probably train a very small model for very specific tasks (placing coral on the reef), but that this would be a demo/teaching tool and probably not a large performance increase.

It will be extremely common for FRC teams to use AI to write code (this year), documentation (this year), and make 3D models (within 3-4 years). I also expect some students have fed the game manual into ChatGPT and had it answer a rules test and generate robot ideas.

Seems like some careful consideration on what to track is in order.

This year has more going on than basically anything we have seen before.

I do agree that being a data input monkey is not fun.

If you are just punching numbers in you are not in the business of “scouting”, you are in the business of “data input”.

kuzeyatay:

Am i too far into the future here or robots will become fully autonomus in the next 5 years?

Unlikely. The nice thing about a human driver is that it is a half-decent physics engine with incredibly low latency while simultaneously being very good at strategies, especially in scenarios they haven’t been trained in (compared to AI), and have (usually) extremely accurate and reliable sensors, while being able to control the robot to its limit in most scenarios.

Even if we just look at the controls problem, in IR&H, the human drivers for most top-level teams were faster than the autonomous routines because making perfectly optimal controls is incredibly hard and well beyond what any high school student or most people with an undergraduate could do. In contrast, driving the robot with a human is so much easier, hence why humans can be very good at driving robots. And that’s disregarding all the strategy stuff which AI really isn’t good at doing without the benefit of human senses.

Alex_Y:

top-level teams were faster than the autonomous routines because making perfectly optimal controls is incredibly hard

In the sake of fariness there are a few (narrow) situations where sequencing beats the snot out of humans. Automated climbs (in their very constrained environments) will almost always win. I expect coral placement to be a similar kettle of fish.

However, these are tasks being performed in isolation, with limited to no knowledge about where game pieces or other robots are on the field. An optimization problem humans excel at.

We may see more automated sequencing as driver aids (e.g. Lane keep assist to grab notes last year). We will never see full auto during teleop. Driving is too fun, games are too complex.

The only year where I think it could have happened is 2015. Do we really want another 2015 so a grand total of 2 teams with the know how can try to play the game with their hands off the controls?

I don’t think ai will play much part in the robots (outside of vision). There are many ways of creating paths on the fly with pure logic (even with dynamic obstacles) that, imo, will always be more reliable than any ai. For more complex games (like this years game) auto scoring is definitely a challenge (in terms of strategy), and would require some amount of human input for strategy, while other years could be done completely based on logic.

Outside of this, I will continue to discourage the use of generative AI for team use. Whether code, archetypes, or strategies, it takes away from the learning experience.
